ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, fresh scales of carp (FS biowaste) were used as the precursors to synthesize FS-CDs (Fig. 1
                        (a)). In general, the initial step of the procedure used 1.0 g of FS biowaste as a precursor for carbon sources. The samples were immersed in 0.5 M Na2CO3 and decalcified with 0.6 M HCl following a previously described procedure [17]. In the second step, the pretreated FS biowaste was utilized as the precursor and subjected to heating in N, N-dimethylformamide (DMF) solvents. FS-CDs were produced after several hours of solvothermal treatment. In order to prepare FS-CDs with strong photoluminescence intensity, the reaction time and temperature were evaluated systematically in a series of experiments. First, the samples were prepared from a different reaction time varying from 6 to 16 h (6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 16 h) at the temperature of 200 °C. The maximum fluorescence intensity of FS-CDs was attained at 8 h (Fig. S1 (a)). Next, the reaction temperature was varied from 140 °C to 220 °C in increments of 20 °C and its influence on the carbon dots fluorescence was evaluated at 8 h. An optimum reaction temperature of 200 °Cwas determined for the FS-CDs synthesis based on the highest fluorescence intensity (Fig. S1 (b). Moreover, the weight of precursor for carbon sources (fresh scales of carp) was adjusted by varying from 0.8 g to 2 g in 20 ml DMF solution. The optimal weight of precursor for carbon sources was experimentally determined to be 1 g. Under the optimal reaction conditions, the absolute fluorescence quantum yields of the as-prepared FS-CDs, which were diluted 100 times and showed less than 0.05 absorbance, were measured by integration sphere of FS5.A fluorescence spectrometer was used to examine the emission characteristics of FS-CDs to further assess their luminescence. The FS-CDs have light yellow emission exposed to 356 nm UV radiations (Fig. S2). As illustrated in Fig. 1(b), the FS-CDs exhibit a strong emission peak at 510 nm upon excitation at 440 nm. It is important to note that the fluorescence of the FS-CDs represent an intensive excitation-dependent emission feature, indicating the appearance of different surface and edge states between the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) energy bands [26]. There is a red shift in the peaks and a drop in the intensity of λem. It is noteworthy to mention that the PLQY of FS-CDs achieved a value of 31.71% (Fig. 1(c)). This is the first report that biomass-based CDs have attained a PLQY above 30% via a one-step solvothermal process. The quantum yield of FS-CDs exhibited a significant advantage over available biomass-derived CDs (Table 2
                        ). The UV–vis absorption spectra of FS-CDs, as depicted in Fig. 1(d), displayed two distinct peaks at approximately 278 nm and 329 nm. The peak at 278 nm can be attributed to the π→π* transition of aromatic CC, while the peak at 329 nm is attributed to the n→π* transition of aromatic CN and CO [27]. The fluorescent lifetime of FS-CDs was determined by conducting measurements using a 357 nm excitation source and monitoring the results at 540 nm, as illustrated in Fig. 1(e). The decay data was accurately modeled by a two-exponential equation, as evidenced by the high determination coefficient (R2 = 0.99786). The average lifetime τ of FS-CDs was determined to be 5.53035 ns, with individual lifetimes τ1 and τ2 measured at 1.66729 ns and 6.97291 ns, respectively. These findings suggest that FS-CDs possess a nanosecond fluorescent lifetime devoid of afterglow or phosphorescence. The investigation assessed the fluorescent stability of FS-CDs across a range of pH values (2–14) as depicted in Fig. S3. The results revealed that FS-CDs demonstrated remarkable photostability in solutions with neutral and basic pH levels (pH 7 to 12). The water solubility of FS-CDs was observed. 1 mg solids of FS-CDs were added to 10 mL water under ultrasonic treatment for 30 min. The FS-CDs were still well soluble in aqueous phase (Fig. S4) and the PLQY of FS-CDs has a value of 21.9% (Fig. S5). The FS-CDs of aqueous phase have a ∼30% lower PLQY, probably due to the loss of fluorophores. The photostability and resistance to photobleaching of FS-CDs were researched. It is found that the fluorescence intensity of the FS-CDs is slightly decreased after 55 days (Fig. S6). The PLQY of FS-CDs has a value of 17.9% (Fig. S7). We infer that the FS-CDs were oxidized in the air is responsible to decrease the fluorescence intensity.
